@node Introduction
@chapter Introduction

Eve is an Emacs major mode for editing spoken-word videos by manipulating text
instead of cutting timelines manually.

@menu
* The Big Idea::
* The Core Workflow::
* About This Manual::
@end menu

@node The Big Idea
@section The Big Idea

Traditional video editing works at the frame level: you scrub a timeline, find
a cut point, and trim.  When your source material is a talking-head recording
or a podcast, almost every edit decision is driven by what was @emph{said} — not by
what is visible.

Eve flips the model.  A Textual Join Manifest (@samp{.tjm.json}) stores your video
as a sequence of transcribed segments, each with per-word timestamps.  You
read and edit the transcript in Emacs.  Delete a word, and it disappears from
the rendered video.  Reorder paragraphs, and the clips follow.  Annotate a
segment with a b-roll clip, and the renderer splices it in.  The text is the
edit.

@node The Core Workflow
@section The Core Workflow

The typical eve session looks like this:

@enumerate
@item
@strong{Transcribe} — run @samp{M-x eve-transcribe} on a directory of raw recordings.
Eve calls @samp{eve transcribe} and opens the resulting @samp{.tjm.json} in eve-mode.

@item
@strong{Edit} — delete filler words (@samp{d}, @samp{f}, @samp{F}), reorder segments (@samp{J}, @samp{K}),
add markers to name sections (@samp{o}), attach b-roll (@samp{b}).

@item
@strong{Preview} — press @samp{C-c SPC} to play the source clip from point, or
@samp{C-c C-c} to compile a draft video in seconds.

@item
@strong{Compile} — @samp{C-c C-c} renders the manifest as an @samp{.mp4}.  Draft renders
are fast (mjpeg, parallel, cached).  @samp{C-u C-c C-c} produces a final
delivery-quality H.264 export.

@item
@strong{Iterate} — the segment cache means only changed segments re-encode.
Speculative pre-rendering warms the cache on every save, so pressing
@samp{C-c C-c} after a small edit is nearly instant.
@end enumerate

@node About This Manual
@section About This Manual

This manual covers the Emacs package (@samp{eve.el}) and the accompanying CLI
(@samp{eve text-edit}, @samp{eve transcribe}).  The normative TJM v1.1 format
specification is in @samp{docs/tjm-spec.md}; this manual cross-references it but
does not reproduce it in full.

