@strong{hydra} (optional) for the @samp{?} keybinding cheatsheet popup
@end itemize

@node Installing the CLI
@subsection Installing the CLI

The @samp{eve} CLI ships as a Python package inside this repository.  On a fresh
clone it bootstraps itself automatically via @samp{scripts/run-cli.sh} using the
pre-built wheel in @samp{cli/dist/} — no @samp{uv} or Python package manager required
at runtime.

To install @samp{eve} globally so @samp{M-x eve-transcribe} can find it:

@example
pip install cli/dist/eve_cli-*.whl
# or with uv:
uv pip install cli/dist/eve_cli-*.whl
@end example

Verify it works:

@example
eve doctor --json
@end example

@node Installing the Emacs package
@subsection Installing the Emacs package

@menu
* straight.el: straightel. 
* Manual::
@end menu

@node straightel
@subsubsection straight.el

@lisp
(use-package eve
  :straight (:type git :host github :repo "behaghel/eve.el"))
@end lisp

@node Manual
@subsubsection Manual

Clone the repository, add it to @samp{load-path}, and require it:

@lisp
(add-to-list 'load-path "/path/to/eve.el")
(require 'eve)
@end lisp

Opening any @samp{*.tjm.json} file then activates @samp{eve-mode} automatically.

@node Accessing the manual in Emacs
@subsection Accessing the manual in Emacs

After installing the package, add the @samp{docs/} directory to Emacs's Info path:

@lisp
(add-to-list 'Info-directory-list
             (expand-file-name "docs" (file-name-directory (locate-library "eve"))))
@end lisp

Then browse the manual with @samp{C-h i m eve RET}.

@node Quick Start
@section Quick Start

This walkthrough takes you from a raw recording to a rendered clip in five
steps.

@enumerate
@item
@strong{Transcribe a recording}

@example
M-x eve-transcribe RET
@end example

Select the directory containing your @samp{.mp4} files.  Eve starts
@samp{eve transcribe} in the background.  When it finishes, the manifest opens
automatically in eve-mode.

@item
@strong{Read through the transcript}

Navigate with @samp{j} / @samp{k}.  The buffer shows each spoken segment as a block
of text.  Timestamps appear in the right margin.

@item
@strong{Delete unwanted content}

Place point on a word and press @samp{d} to delete it.  Press @samp{D} to delete the
whole segment.  Press @samp{f} on a word to tag it as a filler; press @samp{F} to
delete all tagged fillers at once.

@item
@strong{Compile a draft preview}

@example
C-c C-c
@end example

Eve validates the manifest, pre-renders changed segments in the background,
and produces a draft @samp{.mp4} in seconds.  Play it back with
@samp{C-u C-c SPC} or your usual player.

@item
@strong{Export for delivery}

@example
C-u C-c C-c
@end example

Compiles at full H.264 quality using the same segment cache.  Only
segments that haven't been cached yet need re-encoding.
@end enumerate

@node The TJM Manifest
@chapter The TJM Manifest

@menu
* Structure::
* How eve-mode renders a manifest::
* The raw JSON companion buffer::
@end menu

@node Structure
@section Structure

A TJM manifest is a JSON file with two top-level arrays:

@itemize
@item
@samp{sources} — a list of media files referenced by the edit.  Each entry has
an @samp{id} used throughout the manifest and a @samp{file} path.

@item
@samp{segments} — the ordered timeline.  Each segment references a source, a
start and end time (in seconds or ticks), and the spoken text.  Optional
fields carry per-word timestamps, b-roll metadata, speaker identity, tags,
and notes.
@end itemize

A minimal manifest:

@example
@{
  "version": 1,
  "sources": [
    @{ "id": "clip01", "file": "raw/recording.mp4" @}
  ],
  "segments": [
    @{
      "id": "clip01-s0001",
      "source": "clip01",
      "start": 12.34,
      "end": 15.60,
      "text": "This is what was said."
    @}
  ]
@}
@end example

The TJM v1.1 specification in @samp{docs/tjm-spec.md} defines every field,
including the tick-based timing model, the edit overlay, and the render
contract.

@node How eve-mode renders a manifest
@section How eve-mode renders a manifest

Eve-mode presents the manifest as readable text.  Each segment is shown as a
paragraph with its text content.  Markers appear as section headings.
Deleted words are hidden by default (toggle with @samp{C-c C-h}).  Per-word
timestamps are hidden unless @samp{C-c C-w} is active.

The buffer is read-only as prose — you interact through keybindings, not
direct text editing.  The underlying JSON is always kept in sync.

@node The raw JSON companion buffer
@section The raw JSON companion buffer

Press @samp{C-c C-o} (@samp{eve-open-raw-json}) to open the underlying JSON in a
companion buffer.  This is useful for low-level inspection or edits that
the structured commands don't cover.  Saving the companion buffer reloads
the eve-mode view.

