@node Two modes draft and final
@section Two modes: draft and final

@samp{C-c C-c} (@samp{eve-compile}) compiles the manifest at draft quality — fast
enough to catch mistakes before committing to a full export.

@samp{C-u C-c C-c} compiles at final quality (H.264 medium/CRF 18) for delivery.

The quality used can be changed permanently with @samp{eve-compile-quality}.

@node Under the hood
@section Under the hood

Eve's rendering pipeline is designed to be fast after the first run:

@itemize
@item
@strong{Quality profiles} — draft uses MJPEG encoding at ultrafast preset; final
uses H.264 at medium preset.  The codec and preset are resolved
automatically from the @samp{--quality} flag.

@item
@strong{Parallel encoding} — segments are encoded concurrently across all available
CPU cores (@samp{eve-compile-jobs}).

@item
@strong{Segment cache} — rendered segments are stored in @samp{.eve-cache/} next to the
manifest, keyed by a SHA-256 hash of the segment's content and encoding
settings.  Unchanged segments are reused; only changed ones re-encode.

@item
@strong{Speculative pre-rendering} — after each save, an idle timer
(@samp{eve-auto-render-idle-seconds}) fires a background render of the segments
that changed.  When you press @samp{C-c C-c}, the cache is already warm and
compilation reduces to a concat step.
@end itemize

@node Pre-flight validation
@section Pre-flight validation

Before starting a render, eve validates the manifest:

@itemize
@item
All source files must exist and be readable.
@item
All b-roll files must exist.
@item
Segment timecodes must be non-negative and end after start.
@item
Words must fall within their segment bounds.
@end itemize

Warnings appear in the echo area.  Errors block compilation unless you
confirm.  Run validation explicitly with @samp{C-c C-v} (@samp{eve-validate}).

If the estimated render time (from the dry-run analysis) exceeds
@samp{eve-compile-confirm-threshold} seconds, eve asks for confirmation.

@node Dry-run analysis
@section Dry-run analysis

Before rendering, eve can report which segments would be re-encoded and
estimate the render time:

@example
eve text-edit manifest.tjm.json --output out.mp4 --dry-run
@end example

The output (JSON with @samp{--json}) includes @samp{total_segments},
@samp{changed_segments}, and @samp{estimated_seconds}.  This information feeds the
pre-flight confirmation prompt.

@node Checkpoint and resume
@section Checkpoint and resume

If a render is interrupted, eve writes a checkpoint file in @samp{.eve-cache/} as
segments complete.  The next run picks up from where it left off: segments
already in the cache are reused, and only the remaining ones are encoded.

Pass @samp{--no-resume} to force a fresh render from scratch.

@node Progressive output
@section Progressive output

With @samp{--partial-every N}, eve writes a partial @samp{<output>.partial.mp4} after
every N segments complete.  A JSON event is emitted on stdout for each
partial file, which Emacs can use to update a live preview.

